data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: `EventProcessor`

### Critical Issues in the Original Code

| Issue | Severity | .NET 8 Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | 🔴 **Breaking** | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — removed in .NET 5+ |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | 🟡 Obsolete | Marked `[Obsolete]` in .NET 7+, unreliable for `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` |
| Signal race condition | 🔴 Bug | Multiple `Enqueue` calls between `WaitOne`/`Reset` → only 1 item dequeued, rest lost |
| No graceful shutdown | 🟡 Design | No `CancellationToken` support, no way to drain the queue |

### Race Condition Explained

```
Thread A: Enqueue("a") → Set()
Thread B: Enqueue("b") → Set()    // before RunLoop wakes
RunLoop:  WaitOne() → Reset() → Dequeue("a")
          WaitOne() ...            // "b" is stuck — no signal pending
```

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

Replace `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock` with `Channel<T>`, and `Thread` with `Task`:

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _processingTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _processingTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (ct.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Graceful shutdown — expected
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async ValueTask StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _processingTask is null) return;

        _channel.Writer.Complete();                          // signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // hard deadline

        try
        {
            await _processingTask;  // wait for drain or cancellation
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item)
    {
        // Your processing logic here
    }
}
```

### Key Migration Decisions

**Why `Channel<T>` over `BlockingCollection<T>`?**
- `Channel` is async-native — no thread blocked on `WaitOne()`
- Thread-safe reads/writes without explicit `lock`
- `ReadAllAsync` drains all items (fixes the race condition)
- Bounded channels add backpressure if needed: `Channel.CreateBounded<string>(100)`

**Why `CancellationToken` over `Thread.Abort()`?**
- Cooperative cancellation is the only supported pattern in .NET 5+
- `Abort()` threw `ThreadAbortException` that could corrupt state; it was always dangerous

**Shutdown sequence:**
1. `Writer.Complete()` → stops accepting new items
2. `ReadAllAsync` drains remaining items in the queue
3. `CancelAfter` enforces a hard timeout if draining takes too long

### If You Must Stay Synchronous

```csharp
// Drop-in replacement using BlockingCollection (synchronous API)
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly BlockingCollection<string> _queue = new();
    private Task? _processingTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _processingTask = Task.Run(() =>
        {
            foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable(_cts.Token))
                Handle(item);
        });
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) => _queue.Add(item);

    public void Stop()
    {
        _queue.CompleteAdding();
        if (!_processingTask?.Wait(5000) ?? true)
            _cts?.Cancel();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _queue.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { }
}
```

### Pitfall Checklist

- ❌ Don't call `Thread.Abort()` — it will throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime, not compile time
- ❌ Don't use `Thread.Interrupt()` — obsolete and unreliable across wait primitives
- ⚠️ If `Handle()` is async, use `await Handle(item)` in the loop — don't fire-and-forget
- ⚠️ If processing order matters, keep the channel unbounded and single-reader (as shown)
- ✅ Always complete/cancel the channel on shutdown to unblock `ReadAllAsync`
